In MLOps, you need to track all your machine learning models - current versions, past versions, and experimental models. Lists help you maintain a centralized repository.

Why use lists?
Multiple models: You might have 10, 50, or 100 models in production
Easy searching: Find a specific model by name, status, or version
Dynamic updates: Add new models, remove old ones, update status
Comparison: Compare accuracy, performance, and metrics across models
Real-world scenario:
Code
You have a company running 3 churn prediction models:
- Model v1.0 (old, 85% accuracy) - deprecated
- Model v2.0 (current, 91% accuracy) - production
- Model v3.0 (new, 94% accuracy) - staging/testing

Using a list, you can:
✓ Quickly find which model is in production
✓ Retrieve historical performance data
✓ Promote best models to production
✓ Rollback to previous versions if new model fails
2. Training Pipeline Orchestration
What is it?
When training a machine learning model, there are multiple sequential steps. Lists help manage and track each step.

Why use lists?
Step tracking: Monitor progress through data loading → cleaning → feature engineering → training → evaluation
Error handling: Know which step failed if something goes wrong
Performance metrics: Measure time taken by each step
Reusability: Store pipeline configurations for different models
Real-world scenario:
Code
Training pipeline for customer churn model:

Step 1: Load raw customer data (50,000 records) - 5 seconds
Step 2: Clean data (remove nulls, duplicates) - 8 seconds
Step 3: Engineer features (create new columns) - 12 seconds
Step 4: Scale features (normalize values) - 3 seconds
Step 5: Train model (fit on data) - 45 seconds
Step 6: Evaluate performance - 2 seconds

Using a list, you can:
✓ Track completion of each step
✓ Calculate total pipeline duration (75 seconds)
✓ Identify bottlenecks (training takes longest)
✓ Retry failed steps automatically
✓ Predict pipeline completion time
3. Experiment Tracking & Logging
What is it?
Data scientists run hundreds of experiments with different models, parameters, and datasets. Lists store all this information for comparison and reproducibility.

Why use lists?
Track all attempts: Every experiment, every hyperparameter combination
Compare results: Which experiment gave the best accuracy?
Reproducibility: Save exact parameters to reproduce any result
History: Understand how your models evolved over time



